    <title>Combined summary - Proof-of-Stake Bitcoin Sidechains</title>
    <updated>2025-12-30T04:00:35.310618+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-February/016642.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2019-01-18 22:59:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>In a series of emails exchanged among developers and enthusiasts on the bitcoin-dev mailing list, a detailed discussion unfolds around the concept and implementation strategies for Bitcoin sidechains, particularly focusing on the use of the Tendermint BFT consensus protocol and the innovative &quot;mainstake&quot; idea. Matt Bell introduces his work on designing Bitcoin sidechains akin to Blockstream's Liquid sidechain but leveraging the Tendermint BFT consensus protocol, commonly utilized in proof-of-stake networks like Cosmos. He shares a design document and solicits feedback for improvements or identification of potential flaws.
ZmnSCPxj responds with the proposal of &quot;mainstake,&quot; an approach that utilizes UTXOs on the Bitcoin blockchain to weigh voting power in the sidechain, suggesting it as a more secure method than self-attesting tokens used by other blockchains. This method envisions the sidechain network accepting stakers from the mainchain based on proofs of mainchain transactions, specifically designed scripts indicating the stake's duration and control.
Further into the discussion, ZmnSCPxj presents a punishment mechanism for double-signing within the sidechain by making the private key (protecting their Bitcoin stake UTXO) vulnerable upon multiple signatures at the same blockheight, drawing an analogy with Discrete Log Contracts used by Oracles to prevent multiple value signings at particular times.
In addition, there is a suggestion for deriving fixed R values to prevent multiple signatures, using standard hierarchical derivation and revealing the staking public key in a specific form to the sidechain network. This approach aims to ensure uniqueness in R values for each blockheight while maintaining signature creation and verification capabilities.
The dialogue also touches upon concerns related to revealed private keys for time-locked funds potentially creating a race to spend, with ZmnSCPxj proposing that if Bitcoin had implemented Replace By Fee (RBF) properly, such races could be won by bidding up fees, favoring the entity offering the highest fee transaction. The conversation elaborates on the security implications of this mechanism, considering the economic disincentive for miners to take bribes from attackers due to the profitability of claiming the staked amount themselves.
Moreover, ZmnSCPxj outlines a proof-of-mainstake sidechain concept without requiring modifications to the Bitcoin mainchain. This concept relies on the analogy of a blockchain being a Merklized singly-linked list, where a chain of single-input single-output transactions forms the sidechain &quot;blockchain.&quot; The proposal includes mechanisms for mainchain-to-sidechain requests, special scripts for staking indications, and considerations for sidechain managing transactions in relation to mainchain fees and block rates.
These discussions encapsulate a blend of technical insights, proposed innovations, and security considerations aimed at enhancing the functionality and integrity of Bitcoin sidechains through collaborative feedback and exploration of new concepts like &quot;mainstake&quot; and unique signature verification techniques.</summary>
